entry.title: Use dedicated polling thread for wayland event
entry.content:
This patch re-enables removed basic logic of using dedicated polling

thread in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/3386963



The patch removed dedicated polling thread and use

prepare/check/dispatch series with wayland client API carefully.

But it turns out there still exists the case of deadlock.

If higher priority GSource than GLibWaylandSource is used then

MessagePumpGlib could get a chance to run chromium tasks without having

called check of GLibWaylandSource because g_main_context_iteration will

not call check function of lower priority GSource if higher priority

GSource is ready.



The deadlock may be happened only when using --in-process-gpu and EGL

wayland backend so dedicated polling thread needs to be for that case.

entry.title: Move ownership of sockets to QuicChromiumPacketReaders
entry.content:
Packet readers and sockets have a 1:1 relationship i.e. every socket

has a reader and each reader is associated with a socket it reads from.

Hence, to simplify the ownership and socket lifetime, we create the

packet reader with the socket, and use it to access the socket whenever

that is needed. This ensures that the list of sockets and

packet readers do not go out of sync.

used.

entry.title: [Payments] Do not dismiss virtual card enroll on page navigation
entry.content:
Before this patch, the virtual card number (VCN) enrollment bottom sheet

would dismiss on page navigation, which is the default behavior for

bottom sheets. However, VCN enroll can happen when a page navigates, so

navigation should not dismiss this bottom sheet.



This patch creates a custom lifecycle for VCN enroll bottom sheet. This

custom lifecycle dismisses the bottom sheet on tab change and layout

change (e.g., going into "tab overview"). The custom lifecycle ignores

page navigations.



After this change, the VCN enrollment bottom sheet does not dismiss on

page navigation.

entry.title: Add more functionality to set local password input element
entry.content:
This element asks the user to enter a local/device password and confirm

it. The element will be used during onboarding/OOBE and on the ChromeOS

settings page.



Previously the element contained only two password inputs and delegated

most functionality to its parent element. With this change, more

functionality resides in the input element:



- Placeholder and error tooltips are now hardcoded in the input

elements, since they're shared between OOBE and settings.

- The element now handles checking the the password complexity and that

the two user-entered values agree.

- The element now handles traversal between the two password inputs

itself, and only fires events when a password input is available

(i.e., when the user-entered password passes validation).



The commit also changes the name of the element from

local-password-input to set-local-password-input, since only the latter

communicates that the element asks for a new password and is not

suitable for asking the user for their existing password.
